<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,690,1686]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,323,1482,1507]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" box="[665,900,1482,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incantata">
<emphasis box="[665,679,1483,1507]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[693,799,1483,1506]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">incantata</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
in the male genitalia, but can be separated from it by the forewing with sparse black spots, the valvella without process and the phallus with a cornutus in the male genitalia. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" box="[297,540,1554,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incantata">
<emphasis box="[297,434,1555,1579]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. incantata</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
, the forewing has dense black spots, the valvella has a setose process arising from base (
<figureCitation box="[277,362,1590,1614]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–42" captionStartId="18.[151,263,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[232,1344,669,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-286@18.[226,1360,637,1922]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39–42. Male genitalia of Scaeosopha spp. 39, S. spinivalvata sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31023; 40, S. tuberculata sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. ZZW08050; 41, S. victoriensis sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 32349; 42, S. incantata Meyrick, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31006." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,690,1686]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,336,1627,1651]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new specific epithet is derived from the Latin prefix 
<emphasis box="[996,1049,1627,1650]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">rari-</emphasis>
= rare, and the word 
<emphasis box="[1297,1412,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">maculatus</emphasis>
= macular, in reference to the forewing having sparse spots and patches.
</paragraph>
